is). University of Monash, Melbourne, Australia.</li><li class="ordered-list--item ds2-5-body-md">Robinson, M., Cleary, P., &amp; Monaghan, J. (2008). Analysis of mixing in a twin cam mixer using smoothed particle hydrodynamics. AIChE Journal, 54(8), 1987-1998.</li><li class="ordered-list--item ds2-5-body-md">Rodriguez-Paz, M., &amp; Bonet, J. (2005). A corrected smooth par- ticle hydrodynamics formulation of the shallow-water equa- tions. Computers and Structures, 83(17-18), 1396-1410.</li><li class="ordered-list--item ds2-5-body-md">Rogers, B., Fujihara, M., &amp; Borthwick, A. G. L. (2001). Adap- tive Q-tree Godunov-type scheme for shallow water equa- tions. International Journal for Numerical Methods in Fluids, 35(3), 247-280.</li><li class="ordered-list--item ds2-5-body-md">Rogers, B. D., Dalrymple, R. A., &amp; Stansby, P. K. (2010). Simulation of caisson breakwater movement using 2-D SPH. Journal of Hydraulic Research, 48(Extra Issue), 135-141.</li><li class="ordered-list--item ds2-5-body-md">Saad, Y., &amp; Schultz, M. H. (1986). GMRES: a generalized min- imal residual algorithm for solving nonsymmetric linear sys- tems. SIAM Journal on Scientific and Statistical Computing, 7(3), 856-869.</li><li class="ordered-list--item ds2-5-body-md">Shao, S. (2006). Incompressible SPH simulation of wave breaking and overtopping with turbulence modeling. Inter- national Journal for Numerical Methods in Fluids, 50, 597-621.</li><li class="ordered-list--item ds2-5-body-md">Shi, Y. L., Ellero, M., Adams, N. A. (2011). SPH implicit turbulence modeling. Proc. 6th SPHERIC Int. Workshop, Hamburg, Germany, 52-58.</li><li class="ordered-list--item ds2-5-body-md">Skillen, A., Lind, S. J., Stansby, P. K., &amp; Rogers, B. D. (2013). Incompressible Smoothed Particle Hydrodynamics (SPH) with reduced temporal noise and generalised Fickian smoothing applied to body-water slam and efficient wave- body interaction. Computer Methods in Applied Mechanics and Engineering, 265, 163-173.</li><li class="ordered-list--item ds2-5-body-md">Souto-Iglesias, A., Delorme, L., Pérez-Rojas, L., &amp; Abril-Pérez, S. (2006). Liquid moment amplitude assessment in sloshing type problems with smooth particle hydrodynamics. Ocean Engineering, 33, 1462-1484.</li><li class="ordered-list--item ds2-5-body-md">Swegle, J. W., Hicks, D. L., &amp; Attaway, S. W. (1995). Smoothed particle hydrodynamics stability analysis. Journal of Compu- tational Physics, 116, 123-134.</li><li class="ordered-list--item ds2-5-body-md">Szewc, K., Pozorski, J., &amp; Tanière, A. (2011). Modeling of natural convection with Smoothed Particle Hydrodynamics: Non-Boussinesq formulation. International Journal on Heat and Mass Transfer, 54(23-24), 4807-4816.</li><li class="ordered-list--item ds2-5-body-md">Takeda, H., Miyama, S. M., &amp; Sekiya, M. (1994). Numer- ical simulation of viscous-flow by Smoothed Particle Hydrodynamics. Progress of Theoretical Physics, 92(5), 939-960.</li><li class="ordered-list--item ds2-5-body-md">Tartakovsky, A. M., Ferris, K. F., &amp; Meakin, P. (2009). Lagrangian particle model for multi-phase flows. Computer Physics Communications, 180, 1874-1881.</li><li class="ordered-list--item ds2-5-body-md">Temam, R. (1968). Une méthode d&#39;approximation des solu- tions des équations de Navier-Stokes. Bulletin de la Société Mathématique de France, 98, 115-152. (in French).</li><li class="ordered-list--item ds2-5-body-md">Toro, E. F. (2009). Riemann solvers and numerical methods for fluid dynamics (3rd ed.). Berlin: Springer.</li><li class="ordered-list--item ds2-5-body-md">Ulrich, C. (2013). Smoothed-Particle-Hydrodynamics simula- tion of port hydrodynamic problems (PhD thesis). Technische Universität Hamburg-Harburg.</li><li class="ordered-list--item ds2-5-body-md">Ulrich, C., Leonardi, M., &amp; Rung, T. (2013). Multi-physics SPH simulation of complex marine-engineering hydrodynamic problems. Ocean Engineering, 64, 109-121.</li><li class="ordered-list--item ds2-5-body-md">Vacondio, R., Mignosa, P. (2009). Incompressible Finite Pointset for free surface flow. Proc. 5th SPHERIC Int. Work- shop, Lausanne, Switzerland, 201-208.</li><li class="ordered-list--item ds2-5-body-md">Vacondio, R., Mignosa, P., &amp; Pagani, S. (2013). 3D SPH numer- ical simulation of the wave generated by the Vajont rockslide. Advances in Water Research, 59, 146-156.</li><li class="ordered-list--item ds2-5-body-md">Vacondio, R., Rogers, B. D., &amp; Stansby, P. K. (2011). Smoothed Particle Hydrodynamics: approximate zero-consistent 2-D boundary conditions and still shallow water tests. Inter- national Journal for Numerical Methods in Fluids, 69(1), 226-253.</li><li class="ordered-list--item ds2-5-body-md">Vacondio, R., Rogers, B. D., &amp; Stansby, P. K. (2012). Accurate particle splitting for SPH in shallow water with shock captur- ing. International Journal for Numerical Methods in Fluids, 69(8), 1377-1410.</li><li class="ordered-list--item ds2-5-body-md">Vacondio, R., Rogers, B. D., Stansby, P. K., &amp; Mignosa, P. (2012). SPH modeling of shallow flow with open bound- aries for practical flood simulation. Journal of Hydraulic Engineering, 138(6), 530-541.</li><li class="ordered-list--item ds2-5-body-md">Vacondio, R., Rogers, B. D., Stansby, P. K., &amp; Mignosa, P. (2013). Shallow water SPH for flooding with dynamic par- ticle coalescing and splitting. Advances in Water Resources, 58, 10-23.</li><li class="ordered-list--item ds2-5-body-md">Vacondio, R., Rogers, B. D., Stansby, P. K., &amp; Mignosa, P. (forthcoming). Variable resolution for SPH in three dimen- sions: towards optimal splitting and coalescing for dynamic adaptivity. Computer Methods in Applied Mechanics and Engineering.</li><li class="ordered-list--item ds2-5-body-md">Vacondio, R., Rogers, B. D., Stansby, P. K., Mignosa, P., &amp; Feldman, J. (2013). Variable resolution for SPH: a dynamic particle coalescing and splitting scheme. Computer Methods in Applied Mechanics and Engineering, 256, 132-148.</li><li class="ordered-list--item ds2-5-body-md">Valizadeh, A., &amp; Monaghan, J. J. (2012). Smoothed particle hydrodynamics simulations of turbulence in fixed and rotat- ing boxes in two dimensions with no-slip boundaries. Physics of Fluids, 24(3), 035107.</li><li class="ordered-list--item ds2-5-body-md">Van Der Vorst, H. A. (1992). Bi-CGSTAB: a fast and smoothly converging variant of Bi-CG for the solution of nonsymmet- ric linear systems. SIAM Journal on Scientific and Statistical Computing, 13(2), 631-644.</li><li class="ordered-list--item ds2-5-body-md">Vaughan, G. L., Healy, T. R., Bryan, K. R., Sneyd, A. D., &amp; Gorman, R. M. (2009). Completeness, conservation and error in SPH for fluids. International Journal for Numerical Meth- ods in Fluids, 56(1), 37-62.</li><li class="ordered-list--item ds2-5-body-md">Vila, J.-P. (1999). On particle weighted methods and smooth particle hydrodynamics. Mathematical Models and Methods in Applied Sciences, 9, 161-209.</li><li class="ordered-list--item ds2-5-body-md">D. Violeau and B.D. Rogers Journal of Hydraulic Research (2015)</li><li class="ordered-list--item ds2-5-body-md">Violeau, D. (2004). One and two-equations turbulent closures for Smoothed Particle Hydrodynamics. Proc. 6th Int. Conf. Hydroinformatics, pp. 87-94.</li><li class="ordered-list--item ds2-5-body-md">Violeau, D. (2012). Fluid Mechanics and the SPH Method. Theory and Applications. Oxford: Oxford University Press.</li><li class="ordered-list--item ds2-5-body-md">Violeau, D., Buvat, C., Abed-Meraïm, K., &amp; de Nanteuil, E. (2007). Numerical modelling of boom and oil spill with SPH. Coastal Engineering, 54, 895-913.</li><li class="ordered-list--item ds2-5-body-md">Violeau, D., &amp; Issa, R. (2006). Numerical modelling of complex turbulent free surface flows with the SPH Lagrangian method: an overview. International Journal for Numerical Methods in Fluids, 53(2), 277-304.</li><li class="ordered-list--item ds2-5-body-md">Violeau, D., &amp; Leroy, A. (2014). On the maximum time step in weakly compressible SPH. Journal of Computational Physics, 256, 388-415.</li><li class="ordered-list--item ds2-5-body-md">Violeau, D., &amp; Leroy, A. (2015). Optimal time step for Incom- pressible SPH. Journal of Computational Physics, 288, 119- 130.</li><li class="ordered-list--item ds2-5-body-md">Violeau, D., Piccon, S., &amp; Chabard, J.-P. (2002). Two attempts of turbulence modelling in Smoothed Particle Hydrodynam- ics. Advances in Fluid Modelling and Turbulence Measure- ments, World Scientific, 339-346.</li><li class="ordered-list--item ds2-5-body-md">Wallin, N., &amp; Johansson, A. V. (2000). An explicit algebraic Reynolds stress model for incompressible and compress- ible turbulent flows. Journal of Fluid Mechanics, 403, 89- 132.</li><li class="ordered-list--item ds2-5-body-md">Welton, W. C., &amp; Pope, S. B. (1997). PDF model calcula- tions of compressible turbulent flows using smoothed particle hydrodynamics. Journal of Computational Physics, 134, 150-168.</li><li class="ordered-list--item ds2-5-body-md">Wendland, H. (1995). Piecewise polynomial, positive definite and compactly supported radial functions of minimal degree. Advances in Computational Mathematics, 4, 389-396.</li><li class="ordered-list--item ds2-5-body-md">Wu, J., Zhang, H., Dalrymple, R. A., &amp; Hérault, A. (2013). Numerical modeling of dam-break flood in city lay- outs including underground spaces using GPU-based SPH Method. Journal of Hydrodynamics, 25(6), 818-828.</li><li class="ordered-list--item ds2-5-body-md">Xu, R., Stansby, P., &amp; Laurence, D. (2009). Accuracy and stability in incompressible SPH (ISPH) based on the projec- tion method and a new approach. Journal of Computational Physics, 228(18), 6703-6725.</li><li class="ordered-list--item ds2-5-body-md">Yue, T., Pearce, F., Kruisbrink, A., &amp; Morvan, H. (2015). Numerical simulation of two-dimensional Kelvin-Helmholtz instability using weakly compressible smoothed particle hydrodynamics. International Journal for Numerical Meth- ods in Fluids, 78, 283-303.</li><li class="ordered-list--item ds2-5-body-md">Zhang, A., Cao, X.-Y., Ming, F., &amp; Zhang, Z.-F. (2013). Investi- gation on a damaged ship model sinking into water based on three dimensional SPH method. Applied Ocean Research, 42, 24-31.</li><li class="ordered-list--item ds2-5-body-md">Zhao, J. (2012). Development of a fast SPH model for non linear shallow water flows: application to coastal flooding and dam breaking (PhD thesis). Ecole Centrale de Nantes, Nantes.</li><li class="ordered-list--item ds2-5-body-md">Zou, S. (2007). Coastal sediment transport simulation by Smoothed Particle Hydrodynamics (PhD thesis). Johns Hop- kins University, Baltimore, MD.</li></ol><button class="ds2-5-button ds2-5-button--extra-small ds2-5-button--full-width js-tc-loswp--references-view-more references--view-more-link" onclick="this.parentElement.classList.add(&#39;references--show-all&#39;);">View more<span class="material-symbols-outlined" style="font-size: 20px" translate="no">arrow_downward</span></button><script>document.addEventListener('DOMContentLoaded', () => {
  function getCookie(name) {
    const value = `; ${document.cookie}`;
    const parts = value.split(`; ${name}=`);
    if (parts.length === 2) return parts.pop().split(';').shift();
  }

  const csrfToken = document.querySelector("[name='csrf-token']")?.content ??
    getCookie('masked_csrf_token');
  if (!csrfToken) {
    throw 'click tracking disabled due to missing CSRF token (button)';
  }

  const options = {"source":"loswp--references-view-more"};
  const button = document.querySelector('.js-tc-loswp--references-view-more');
  button.addEventListener('click', () => {
    fetch('/v0/clicks?subdomain_param=api', {
      method: 'POST',
      headers: {
        'Content-Type': 'application/json',
        'X-CSRF-Token': csrfToken,
      },
      keepalive: true,
      mode: 'same-origin',
      body: JSON.stringify({
        ...options,
        occurred_at: new Date(),
        hit_id: window.Aedu?.hit_data?.id,
      }),
    });
  });
});</script></div><div class="work-faq--container"><div class="work-faq--heading-container"><h2 class="work-faq--heading ds2-5-heading-sans-serif-lg" id="faq">FAQs</h2><div class="ai-label"><img alt="sparkles" src="//a.academia-assets.com/images/icons/sparkle.svg" width="16" height="16" /><p class="ds2-5-body-xs">AI</p></div></div><div class="work-faq--list"><details class="work-faq--item" data-faq-number="1"><summary class="work-faq--question js-faq-question"><span class="work-faq--question-text" data-question="Why is SPH considered effective for simulating complex free-surface flows?">Why is SPH considered effective for simulating complex free-surface flows?</span><span class="material-symbols-outlined work-faq--icon" style="font-size: 18px" translate="no">add</span></summary><div class="work-faq--answer"><p class="ds2-5-body-md">SPH demonstrates superior ability to handle highly nonlinear, inertia-dominated flows and distorted free surfaces, validated through numerous case studies since the mid-1990s.</p></div></details><details class="work-faq--item" data-faq-number="2"><summary class="work-faq--question js-faq-question"><span class="work-faq--question-text" data-question="What advances in SPH theory address its previously identified drawbacks?">What advances in SPH theory address its previously identified drawbacks?</span><span class="material-symbols-outlined work-faq--icon" style="font-size: 18px" translate="no">add</span></summary><div class="work-faq--answer"><p class="ds2-5-body-md">Recent developments focus on computational efficiency using GPGPUs, density filtering, and shock-capturing techniques to improve stability and accuracy in simulations.</p></div></details><details class="work-faq--item" data-faq-number="3"><summary class="work-faq--question js-faq-question"><span class="work-faq--question-text" data-question="How does SPH methodology differ from traditional mesh-based numerical methods?">How does SPH methodology differ from traditional mesh-based numerical methods?</span><span class="material-symbols-outlined work-faq--icon" style="font-size: 18px" translate="no">add</span></summary><div class="work-faq--answer"><p class="ds2-5-body-md">SPH employs a Lagrangian framework following fluid particles without mesh constraints, allowing for more flexible modeling of fluid dynamics.</p></div></details><details class="work-faq--item" data-faq-number="4"><summary class="work-faq--question js-faq-question"><span class="work-faq--question-text" data-question="What are some of the primary applications of SPH in hydraulic research?">What are some of the primary applications of SPH in hydraulic research?</span><span class="material-symbols-outlined work-faq--icon" style="font-size: 18px" translate="no">add</span></summary><div class="work-faq--answer"><p class="ds2-5-body-md">SPH has been successfully applied to oil spill dynamics, groundwater flow stability, and multi-phase flows involving sediment scouring, showing significant promise in these areas.</p></div></details><details class="work-faq--item" data-faq-number="5"><summary class="work-faq--question js-faq-question"><span class="work-faq--question-text" data-question="What are the future challenges for SPH in hydraulic and environmental engineering?">What are the future challenges for SPH in hydraulic and environmental engineering?</span><span class="material-symbols-outlined work-faq--icon" style="font-size: 18px" translate="no">add</span></summary><div class="work-faq--answer"><p class="ds2-5-body-md">Key challenges include establishing rigorous boundary conditions, improving turbulence modeling, and enhancing multi-phase flow capabilities, identified as essential for broadening SPH applications.</p></div></details></div></div><script>document.addEventListener('DOMContentLoaded', () => {
  function getCookie(name) {
    const value = `; ${document.cookie}`;
    const parts = value.split(`; ${name}=`);
    if (parts.length === 2) return parts.pop().split(';').shift();
  }

  const csrfToken = document.querySelector("[name='csrf-token']")?.content ??
    getCookie('masked_csrf_token');
  if (!csrfToken) {
    throw 'click tracking disabled due to missing CSRF token (FAQ)';
  }

  const faqQuestions = document.querySelectorAll('.js-faq-question');
  const numberedFaqs = [{"answer":"SPH demonstrates superior ability to handle highly nonlinear, inertia-dominated flows and distorted free surfaces, validated through numerous case studies since the mid-1990s.","question":"Why is SPH considered effective for simulating complex free-surface flows?","number":1},{"answer":"Recent developments focus on computational efficiency using GPGPUs, density filtering, and shock-capturing techniques to improve stability and accuracy in simulations.","question":"What advances in SPH theory address its previously identified drawbacks?","number":2},{"answer":"SPH employs a Lagrangian framework following fluid particles without mesh constraints, allowing for more flexible modeling of fluid dynamics.","question":"How does SPH methodology differ from traditional mesh-based numerical methods?","number":3},{"answer":"SPH has been successfully applied to oil spill dynamics, groundwater flow stability, and multi-phase flows involving sediment scouring, showing significant promise in these areas.","question":"What are some of the primary applications of SPH in hydraulic research?","number":4},{"answer":"Key challenges include establishing rigorous boundary conditions, improving turbulence modeling, and enhancing multi-phase flow capabilities, identified as essential for broadening SPH applications.","question":"What are the future challenges for SPH in hydraulic and environmental engineering?","number":5}];
  const workId = 36004887;

  function trackFaqClick(faqNumber) {
    fetch('/v0/clicks?subdomain_param=api', {
      method: 'POST',
